Ford GoBike System Data¶

by H.YUAN¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Bike-sharing is gaining popularity, since it provides a convenient solution for short distance transportation, especially where the typical public transportation systems could not cover thoroughly. Riders can pick up a bike from one station and drop off at any other in the network. In return the system can keep on operating with income from: 1. rider membership fee, or 2. one time pay-to-ride rental fee.

This document explores a dataset containing information about individual rides of Ford GoBike sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Gathering¶

The data can be directly downloaded from Ford GoBike. Data for 2017 is packed up in one CSV file, and for 2018 there are seperate files of each month from Jan. to Nov. I want to take a look of the latest data over a whole year, namely from Dec. 2017 to Nov. 2018, therefore, it requires some data wrangling to get one complete dataset.

def convert_data_type(dataframe, col, datatype):
    mask = dataframe[col].notnull()
    if datatype == 'str':
        dataframe.loc[mask, col] = dataframe.loc[mask, col].astype('int').astype('str')
    if datatype == 'int':
        dataframe.loc[mask, col] = dataframe.loc[mask, col].astype('int')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 181,8897 trips recorded for the last one year from 2017.12 to 2018.11. The data consists of 15 columns covering various details from trip duration, start/end time, start/end station name and GPS location, to user information for each trip:

  1. trip: duration, time stamp, start/end location
  2. user: age, gender, type
  3. station: geographical distribution, traffics

Among those, duration is numeric, station- and user-related data are mostly categorical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this project, I want to know about user demand for this bike sharing system, by focusing on:

  1. user behavior: duration, time stamps -> time-related patterns
  2. station activity: routes, pick-ups (outflow), drop-offs (inflow) -> geographical concentration, tidal traffic pattern

The key to interpret the data is to calculate trip counts regarding the two aspects above.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the user demands during weekday and weekend are different, so I need to take a look at the time stamp and divide the trips into different groups. Moreover, this step is also necessary when examing the station traffics to look for tidal traffic patterns.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I would like to take on the following questions:

  1. When are most trips taken in terms of time of day, day of the week, or month of the year?
  2. How long on average does one trip take in terms of time of day, day of the week, or month of the year?
  3. How does the trip count vary with different user groups?
  4. How does the inflow (# of drop-offs) and outflow (# of pick-ups) at the most popular stations differentiate?

Q1&2: To answer these questions, I need to first extract the key features about time of day (hour), day of week, month out of column start_time or end_time.

def agg_plot(df, cat_var, num_var):
    """Plot the aggregated values of interest by certain time base"""
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = [16,4])
    agg_val0 = df.groupby(cat_var).size()
    agg_val0 = agg_val0.reset_index(name = 'trip_count')
    agg_val1 = df.groupby(cat_var)
    
    g1 = sb.barplot(data=agg_val0, x=cat_var, y='trip_count', color=base_color, ax=ax[0])
    ax[0].set_ylabel('trip count')
    ticks0 = np.arange(0,350000,50000)
    labels0 = [0, '50k', '100k', '150k', '200k', '250k', '300k']
    ax[0].set_yticks(ticks0)
    ax[0].set_yticklabels(labels0)
    
    g2 = sb.boxplot(data=df, x=cat_var, y=num_var, color=base_color)
    ax[1].set_yscale('log')
    ax[1].set_ylabel('duration')
    ax[1].set_yticklabels([])
#    ticks1 = [300, 600, 900, 1200]
#    labels1 = ['5min', '10min', '15min', '20min']
#    ax[1].set_yticks(ticks1)
#    ax[1].set_yticklabels(labels1)
    ax[1].set_ylim(300,1200)
    
    if cat_var != 'day_of_week':
        if cat_var == 'year_month':
            locs, labels = plt.xticks()
            ticks = locs
            labels = ['Dec','Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov']
            ax[0].axvline([0.5], ls='--', color='r')
            ax[1].axvline([0.5], ls='--', color='r')
        if cat_var == 'hour':
            hours = np.arange(0,24,1)
            ticks = hours
            labels = ['{}'.format(hr) for hr in ticks]
        for i in range(2):
                ax[i].set_xticks(ticks)
                ax[i].set_xticklabels(labels)

  • The monthly results indicate a seasonal alternation period that less trips are made from January to April than from May to October, which then followed by a decrease in November (expected to be the same also in Decemeber). This is not surprising.
  • The weekly results indicate that more trips are taken during weekdays, but shorter on average comparing to weekends, maybe due to different usages. During weekdays, people may take more short trips for commutes, however during weekends more longer trips for sightseeing, shopping etc.
  • The hourly result shows two peaks: one around 8 a.m. and one around 17 p.m., both are typical rush hours for morning/night commutes.

def slopegraph(df, num):
    """Plot the slopegraph"""
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(5, 14))
    # These are the colors that will be used in the plot
    color_sequence = sb.color_palette('Blues_d',num)

    # Remove the plot frame lines. They are unnecessary here.
    ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['bottom'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)
    
    ax.get_xaxis().tick_bottom()
    ax.get_yaxis().tick_left()
    ax.get_xaxis().set_ticks([])
    ax.get_yaxis().set_ticks([])
    
    # Sort the dataframe with descending orders of inflow.
    ldf = df.sort_values(by='total_traffic_volume', ascending=False).loc[:num-1,:].reset_index(drop=True)
    left = 'inflow'
    right = 'outflow'
#    print(ldf.head(num))
    for i in range(num):
        line = plt.plot([0,1], [ldf.loc[i,left], ldf.loc[i,right]], 
                        lw=2, color=color_sequence[i])
        y_left_pos = ldf.loc[i,left] + y_left_offset[i]
        y_right_pos = ldf.loc[i,right] + y_right_offset[i]
        plt.text(-0.15,y_left_pos, str(ldf.loc[i,left]))
        plt.text(-0.35,y_left_pos, ldf.loc[i,'station_id'])
        plt.text(1+0.03,y_right_pos, str(ldf.loc[i,right]))
        plt.text(1+0.2,y_right_pos, ldf.loc[i,'station_name'])
    
    plt.text(-0.18,max(ldf.loc[0,left],ldf.loc[0,right])*1.015, 'INFLOW\ndrop-offs')
    plt.text(-0.4,max(ldf.loc[0,left],ldf.loc[0,right])*1.015, 'station ID\n')
    plt.text(1,max(ldf.loc[0,left],ldf.loc[0,right])*1.015, 'OUTFLOW\n pick-ups')

So the slopegraph shows that some of the most popular stations, especially those with greatest user demands, may suffer from imbalances between pick-ups and drop-offs, which may require additional rellocations of bikes, in order to make the most use of them. This also indicates that the traffic flow has certain direction, whether it is tidal or not can only be determined by introducing time variable.

Further investigation about rellocations can be conducted by tracking the bike ID, to see if there are station jumps, meaning a bike is dropped off at one station, but in the next trip starts from a different one. This will not be conducted here in this project.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Q1: The bar charts of trip counts against different time measurements indicate that In total most of trips are taken during rush hours, weekdays and warm seasons. Since that rush hour commutes don't apply for weekends, I need to isolate hour and day of week next, in order to check the difference between weekdays and weekends.

Q2: The median of trip duration seems to be shorter during weekdays than weekends.

Q3: User gender and subscription status do correlate with trip counts, more trips are made by male users and subscribers respectively.

Q4: The slopegraph shows how the station traffics in total looks like, with information about the inflow (drop-offs), outflow (pick-ups), and the gap in between. It also indicates that user demand varies from station to station, and stations with the greatest user demands tend to have bigger gap between inflow and outflow, manual rellocation should be required.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There seems to be an inverse relation between trip duration and trip counts. Although there are more trips during rush hours, but the median of duration is shorter than normal daytime. When looking at the results on a weekly base, the median duration is longer on weekends than weekdays. Maybe less people tend to ride longer routes on weekends, and more users ride shorter routes during weekdays for different purposes, such as sightseeing comparing to daily commutes.

def agg_plot_3(df0, cat_var, num_var='duration_sec', time_base='hour'):
    
    df1 = df0.groupby([cat_var, time_base]).size()/52
    df1 = df1.reset_index(name='mean_trip_count')
    
    df2 = df0.groupby([cat_var, time_base])[num_var].mean()
    df2 = df2.reset_index(name='mean_duration_sec')
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = [14,5])
    sb.pointplot(data = df1, x = time_base, y = 'mean_trip_count', hue = cat_var,
           palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '', ax=ax[0])
    sb.pointplot(data = df2, x = time_base, y = 'mean_duration_sec', hue = cat_var,
           palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '-', ax=ax[1])
    ax[0].set_ylabel('mean trip count')
    ax[1].set_ylabel('mean trip duration (sec)')

def gps_plot(num_var, boundary, gain, axes):
    x1,x2 = boundary[0]
    y1,y2 = boundary[1]
    popularity = station_traffics[num_var]/gain
    
    axes.scatter(x='station_longitude', y='station_latitude', data=station_traffics, alpha=1/2, s=popularity);
    axes.set_xlim(x1,x2)
    axes.set_ylim(y1,y2)
    axes.set_xlabel('longitude')
    axes.set_ylabel('latitude')
    axes.grid(True, which='both')

In [70]:
def traffics(flag):
    
    mask = fgb_df_clean.weekday == flag
    days = fgb_df_clean.loc[mask,:].date.nunique()
    # aggregate and transform the data of stations setting as start location
    # trip counts start from each station is renamed as outflow
    stout = (fgb_df_clean.loc[mask,:].groupby(['start_station_name']).size()).apply(lambda x: round(x,2))
    stout = stout.reset_index(name='outflow')
    stout.rename(lambda x: x.replace('start_', ''), axis='columns', inplace=True)
    # aggregate and transform the data of stations setting as end location
    # trip counts start from each station is renamed as inflow
    stin = (fgb_df_clean.loc[mask,:].groupby(['end_station_name']).size()).apply(lambda x: round(x,2))
    stin = stin.reset_index(name='inflow')
    stin.rename(lambda x: x.replace('end_', ''), axis='columns', inplace=True)
    # merge dataframe
    traffics = stout.merge(stin, on='station_name', how='inner')
    traffics = traffics.merge(stations_df, on='station_name', how='inner')
    traffics['total_traffic_volume'] = traffics['inflow'] + traffics['outflow']
    
    return traffics

def plot_busiest_station_traffic(df, rank):
    # Sort the dataframe with descending orders of total_traffic_volume.
    traffics = df.sort_values(by='total_traffic_volume', ascending=False).loc[:19,:].reset_index(drop=True)
    stations = traffics.station_name[:19]
    
    station = stations[rank-1]
    weeks = 52
    df1 = fgb_df_clean[fgb_df_clean.end_station_name == station]
    df2 = fgb_df_clean[fgb_df_clean.start_station_name == station]
    dfin = (df1.groupby(['hour','day_of_week']).size()/weeks).reset_index(name='inflow')
    dfout = (df2.groupby(['hour','day_of_week']).size()/weeks).reset_index(name='outflow')
    
    busiest_station = dfin.merge(dfout, on=['hour', 'day_of_week'])
    busiest_station.loc[:,'outflow'] = - busiest_station.loc[:,'outflow']
    busiest_station['net_flow'] = busiest_station.loc[:,'inflow'] + busiest_station.loc[:,'outflow']
    station_traffic_stats = busiest_station.groupby('hour').agg('mean').reset_index()
    
    base_colors = sb.color_palette()
    plt.figure(figsize=[9,4])
    plt.subplot(2,1,1)
    g1 = sb.barplot(data=station_traffic_stats, x='hour', y='inflow', color=base_colors[0]);
    g2 = sb.barplot(data=station_traffic_stats, x='hour', y='outflow', color=base_colors[1]);
    plt.title('Traffic at {}'.format(station));
    plt.ylabel('pick-ups & drop-offs')
    plt.subplot(2,1,2)
    g3 = sb.barplot(data=station_traffic_stats, x='hour', y='net_flow', color=base_colors[2], alpha=0.7);
    
    plt.figure()
    g = sb.FacetGrid(data=busiest_station, row='day_of_week', height=2, aspect=4)
    base_colors = sb.color_palette()
    #plt.title('Traffic at {}'.format(station));
    g.map(sb.barplot, 'hour', 'inflow', color=base_colors[0]);
    g.map(sb.barplot, 'hour', 'outflow', color=base_colors[1]);
    g.add_legend()
    plt.ylabel('pick-ups & drop-offs')

def routes(flag):
    
    mask = fgb_df_clean.weekday == flag
    days = fgb_df_clean.loc[mask,:].date.nunique()
    
    routes = fgb_df_clean.loc[mask,:].groupby(['start_station_name', 'end_station_name']).size()
    routes = routes.reset_index(name='count')
    routes.sort_values(['count'], ascending=False, inplace=True)
    routes = routes.reset_index(drop=True)
    
    return routes

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I took a look at the traffics of the busiest station (San Francisco Caltrain Station 2), due to morning/afternoon commutes, there are more activities on weekday than weekend, furthermore, there are more bikes being picked up in the morning and more dropped off in the afternoon, this is typical tidal traffic pattern. However it doesn't give us any information about the pattern on weekends, so I took out the busiest station during weekends, and did the same analysis. On the contrary, more drop-offs in the morning and more pick-ups in the afternoon, without weekday commutes, the tendency is similar but with only one peak for pick-ups and drop-offs separately.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

All the results fit my anticipations for the dataset. However due to the limit of time, I only explore the most taken routes on weekdays and weekends with list. Surprisingly, only the 10th of the top 10 busiest routes include the busiest station San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 as end station. I assume that the total traffic volume of this station is more spread out through all connecting routes on average, therefore do not stand out like the other nine.
